 TitleBar.image is copyright 2001 by Massimo Tantignone (notice that from
 Homer 1.1 TitleBar.image is no longer included in this archive, but if
 you have it installed in your system, NewHomer will use it. This is the
 case for ie VisualPrefs users).


 NewHomer is totally freeware. It may be freely distributed as long as these
 conditions are both met:

 1) the file in the archive are not modified in any way
 2) it is NOT used for commercial purposes and/or user have to pay for it

This excludes distribution in Amiga magazines coming with a CD: NewHomer can
(repeat: can) be distributed in such way.

 The author is NOT RESPONSIBLE for any damage that may occur for proper
 and improper use of this program... this needs to be said I think, but
 the program seems to be much stable, so you can sleep safe nights ;)).
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

 Requirements
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~
 In short:

 - OS 3.0 or better
 - some picture.datatype and ILBM decoder
 - some sound.datatype and WAVE decoder
   even if I STRONGLY suggest you to download v41 sound and wave
   datatypes... please have a look at @{"limitations" linkk "Limitations"} too.
 - the old Homer 1.5/1.6 and its set of sample, or a new set, such as
   NewHomer_DATA.lha that I put on Aminet).

  You can convert samples and pictures to any datatype format you have,
  if you don't have ILBM/WAVE... but it would be quite strange, at
  least for ILBM, made even from Commodore itself (miracle!).

 In long:

 You have two options here: you can install NewHomer over the old Homer
 1.6 from Aminet, OR you can download the NewHomer_DATA.lha data file
 and install the whole thing from scratch, with the installer found in
 the NewHomer.lha archive.

 (italian users: I've made a NewHomer_ITA_DATA.lha file that has many
 funny samples from the italian version of the Simpsons... unfortunately
 it has been put on Aminet with a slight different name... her that was
 my fault, I gave a too long name to it. Search "NewHomer" and you
 should find everything, though.)

 I also SUGGEST to download the #?_Data.lha file and install from
 scratch, since I had one bug report of NewHomer not working at all on top
 of an old Homer installation. It IS compatible to the old one, but only
 if the old Homer.conf config file has not strange modifications.

 NOTE: the audio.device option DO NOT WORKED (I guess if they ever had).
       id est: standard audio.device WILL ALWAYS BE used. This is done
       since I don't think there are other devices strictly compatible to it.

       If someone really needs to have,e.g.,AHI device support, please drop
       @{"me" link "Author" 0} a line.

       These options are still there and won't cause any trouble, do
       whatever you want with them.

 Then you need AmigaOS 3.0+ (V39).

 Remember _NOT_TO_CHANGE_ the names of data files to anything else than
 "HomerAnim.gif" and "HomerDictionary.gif", EVEN if you save them in a
 different format than GIF (infact they are IFF-ILBM files currently...
 but you know, Amiga Os is not that nasty extension-sensitive! :)) Doing
 anything else won't make your Amiga explode, just NewHomer won't start
 or won't show the help picture... ;)

 Oh, and you need, of course, an Amiga. Don't know if it works on UAE, if
 someone tries it and want to let @{"me" link "Author" 0} know...
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation "

 Installation
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 The installation is quite difficult and should not be permormed by
 beginners... :-D Joking, as you've noticed, haven't you??

 There's an installer script that SHOULD work good. You can install over
 the previous Homer installation and delete it or you can install it
 from scratch using the "NewHomer_DATA.lha" that I've provided for this
 on Aminet. If you didn't have old Homer and you still want to install this
 one, just download the other file and start the installation script
 choosing 'New Installation' when prompted.

 If you want to install by hand over the old Homer, you have to copy the
 "NewHomer" executable file to the old Homer directory, and change the
 tooltypes accordingly. Plus, if you are using the NewHomer_DATA.lha file,
 you can copy the new HomerAnim.gif and HomerDict.gif files (they ARE
 two IFF pictures despite their names) if you don't have a GIF datatype.
 Those names were mantained due to compatibility with old Homer.

 If you installed it over the previous version and you want to use the new
 features, you have to edit the 'Homer.conf' file manually. Look at the
 @{"config" link "Configuration" 0} pages to see how it works.

 Now you can delete the following files from old Homer distrubution in case
 you want:

   Homer - main program
   libs/swazconfig.library and libs/matrix.library - if you are sure
                                  no other program uses these libs, and
                                  they are still in the libs: directory,
                                  you can delete them forever...

 at this point you can rename NewHomer to Homer, if you want.

 Now, look to the @{"configuration" link "Configuration" 0} page and @{"enhancements" link "Enhancements" 0} page, to see
 what's new with NewHomer and how you can get the most from it!
@endnode

@node "Enhancements" "Enhancements "
@next "Configuration"
@prev "Installation"

 Enhancements
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 This new version does exactly the same as old funny Homer did (well,
 there's just one big @{"difference" link "Differences" 0}, look at changes).

 The other nice things are: iconification, separate eyes movement, side audio
 channel allocation according to window position, the possibility to make Homer
 shut up, window resizable on the fly and finally the ability to turn his
 face left/right with the right mouse button...

 Oh and now you can edit the following attributes in the  config file (click
 @{"HERE" system "ed NewHomer.conf"} to edit the configuration file right now!).

 Click @{"HERE" system "multiview NewHomer.conf"} to view the config file for
 an explanation of the other options available.

 - ActivateWindow: setting this to 1, will activate Homer window at program
      (V1.83)      startup. Defaults to 0.

 - AudioVolume:  this will set the audio.device volume to the value specified.
                 Please notice that only values 0-64 make sense. Higher values
                 will be clipped down to 64 (max), that is also the default
                 value.

                 Notice that "AudioDevice" parameters (including unit and
                 priority, have been disabled forever - actually I can't
                 remember if I ever added support for them).

 - DelayTime: this will set the time (in seconds) that has to pass between
              two sentences... Now I hope that people who thought that
              Homer was talking too much, will have enough parameters to
              play with in order to make Homer as nice as they want... :)
              Defaults to 8.

----
 - DoPleasure: this number is the weighted probability for Homer to play a 
               sample from the [PleasureSample] list.

WARNING THIS OPTIONS WAS _NOT_ WORKING AT ALL BEFORE (V1.85).

(look at @{"config file" system "Multiview Newhomer.conf" 0} to see
 how it works now).
----

 - FinalMood: this is quite like "InitialMood"; The difference is that 0 means
              keep current mood, so it is only "pseudo" random.
              There are TWO more significant values: 5 means do a belch, 6 do
              a "d'oh" (forgot to signal in V1.84).

 - FollowMouse: this is new for version 1.6. Just set this to a non zero
                value, and Homer will follow automatically the mouse
                pointer turning his head left or right; this will make the
                'LookLeft' option unuseful. If you have a very slow machine
                and still care about multitasking, then don't set this. On my
                Amiga with a 060, many bitmap's flipping won't make much
                difference, but I think that on a mere 68000 doing that
                would slow down (if, ie, you are working in another screen
                and you continually move the mouse over Homer's window
                position, the most compute-intensive routine of the program
                will be called!!).
                From V1.85 Homer will follow the mouse even while he is
                talking. Nice way to steal some more cycles from your CPU! ;)

 - FrameWidth: this is the horizontal size of an animation frame. This can
               be used in order to have a bigger self-made Homer animation
               for example. However, it needs also FrameHeight, plus some
               other things (eye positions and sizes...), so it is still
               not working.
               I suggest not to change these values anyway, since there's
               not yet support for different eye position than the
               built in ones (now an eye of 1 pixel fits good into an
               eye of a 26x32 pixels frame). So, these could get useful
               in a @{"future" link "Future" 0} release.

 - IconifyMood: Like before, the moods of Homer when he plays a sample before
 DeIconifyMood  or after being iconified. See also "[IconifySamples]".
   (V1.85)

 - [IconifySamples]: this is a set of samples to be played when NewHomer goes
 [DeIconifySamples]: iconified or returns. I suggest you to use short samples
       (V1.85)       only. See also "(De)IconifyMood".

 - LookLeft: this indicates if homer should start looking left or right
             when the window is opened for the first time. Possible
             values: 0 (look right) or 1 (look left).

 - NoExitSample: when you quit Homer, the sample "PROGDIR:samples/outahere"
    (V1.83)      will be played. If you don't want to play the exit sample,
                 please write anything but a blank string here (ie anything
                 different from just space chars :) will be good).

 - [PleasureSamples]: here you can set the list of "mmm" samples :)) This
                      could have worked with old Homer too, but the Homer
                      author never added it. If you don't like this too,
                      set the DoPleasure parameter to 0 and remove all the
                      samples from this list (only if you installed the
                      NewHomer.conf config file, old homer.conf didn't have
                      this).

 - ScaleFactorX: thanks to Fabrizio Bartoloni ;)) I remembered there may be
                 some people out there still using 'odd' screen
                 resolutions such as PAL 640x256 or 320x512... (well I hope
                 NOBODY uses this last one!). Give a look at the extended
                 configuration file and set this param. accordingly, so no
                 more 'slim' or too 'fat'...) Homers from now on!

- SaveMem: this parameter controls how NewHomer shall allocate the flipped
  (V1.85)  bitmap (when Homer turns). It is OFF by default (ie Homer will
           allocate the flipped bitmap at startup in any case). Setting it to
           non-zero, will spare about 7k with the standard animation.

 - [StartSamples]: if this list is present with valid sample names, Homer
       (V1.83)     will play the named file at program startup. Defaults
                   to no file.

 - StartSampleMood: This will set the mood for the start sample animation.
       (V1.85)      Notice it can be also do a belch (=5) or a "d'oh" (=6).

 - [EndSamples]: as above, these will be played at the end. Defaults to sample
      (V1.83)    "outahere" and this WILL be played unless NoExitSample is
                 non zero.
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Enhancements"

 Configuration
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

 First, look at the original Homer documentation if you have it, or read
 the #?.conf file (it is enough self-explaining...).

 Just @{"read" system "multiview newhomer.conf"} that file, plus, if you want to disable a file from the config,
 you can put a "D" letter after its name (eg: "BartBeer D" would disable
 the sample named "BartBeer").

 --FIX for V1.87: any word after a sample name (with space or tab as a
                  separator), would have disabled that sample. Only comments
                  now (starting with a '#') are admitted after a sample name.
                  Sorry but the config file is not that powerful. A gui and a
                  compact config file would be far better, please wait...

 Then, look at the @{"enhancements" link "Enhancements" 0} page: here
 it is explained how to do to edit the Homer.conf file in order to have
 the new features enabled.

 Then you can edit the following tooltypes for the NewHomer.info icon,
 but only if you need it, since the installer will do it automatically.

 CONFIG=Homer.conf

 this can be set to whatever you like... thogh values that make sense are
 Homer.conf, and NewHomer.conf. All file names will be taken as relative to
 "PROGDIR:" path (see below).

 ****Fixed: the name can now be put inside quotes and contain spaces
 (well, it could have contained spaces even before, but people usually
 write file names with spaces within quotes under AmigaDOS... and in the
 previous version this didn't work! ;))

 Examples:

 CONFIG=NewHomer_Ita.conf
 CONFIG=NewHomer Ita.conf
 CONFIG="NewHomer Ita.conf"
 CONFIG='NewHomer ita.conf'

 Defaults to: "Homer.conf" (compatibility to the old Homer).

 DONOTWAIT

 well this is useful for those who want to put homer into the WbStartup
 drawer.

 PROGDIR=work:homer

 this is a path to the location where homer is installed. It is set by
 default by the installer. IT IS ONLY required when you put the executable
 in another directory (eg sys:WbStartup). You can remove it if you leave the
 executable in the same directory where the data are installed.

 ****Fixed: now you can use any 'normal' ;) pattern you want, with quotes
 or not. The following examples are all perfectly legal:

 PROGDIR="Work:Homer/"
 PROGDIR='Work:Homer'
 PROGDIR=Work:My Homer
 PROGDIR='Work:My Homer/'
 PROGDIR="Work:My Homer" (this would be the most used I think...)

 Defaults to... PROGDIR: :)) ie the directory NewHomer was started from.

 FBLIT (new for version 1.6)

 This will use normal BltBitMap() to scale the animation on the y axis
 when ScaleFactorX is 100 AND an AGA/ECS screen WITHOUT CyberGfx/P96 is
 used. If you have installed a program like FBlit and have a powerful
 enough CPU, this 'could' speed up a bit under that strange situation...

 PUBSCREEN (V1.84)

 This can be used to let Homer's window open on a screen different from the
 Workbench. Defaults to the default :) pubscreen, usually Workbench.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "Hints"
@prev "Configuration"

 Usage
 ~~~~~

  With the mouse

 - Click into Homer window to make him talk/shut up.
 - Click the iconify gadget to iconify the window (oh,great I didn't
   know! :)
 - If you click the window just after Homer belchs or says d'oh, it will repeat
   it.
 - Click the close gadget to quit (this was the most difficult thing wasn't
   it? :))
 - Click with RIGHT mouse button to turn Homer left/right when its window
   is active. Note: starting with version 1.6, this won't work if the option
   "FollowMouse" is active, since the latter wouldn't make much sense other-
   wise...
 - Click with MIDDLE mouse button to force Homer talking (and not repeating
   dohs and burps) V1.81 ONLY - UNTESTED.
 - Click and drag in the bottom right corner of the window to resize it.
 - Click and drag in the left part of the window to move it (do this just in
   case the titlebar is full with gadgets).

  From the keyboard:

 - Press the ESC key to quit
 - Press the I key to iconify Homer
 - Press the space bar to shut up Homer if he is talking
 - Press RETURN, ENTER, to make him talk/shut up (from V1.81 Homer won't
   repeat actions like burps and dohs, but just talk).
 - Press the Help key to know who Homer is ;))
 - Press 'd' and 'b' keys to... find out by yourselves (hint, try first the
   'd' key, and try to figure it out what the 'b' is for before using it...).
 - Press 'f' key to flip the bitmap and make Homer turn left/right (V1.85).
@endnode

@node "Hints" "Hints"
@next "Differences"
@prev "Usage"

 Hints
 ~~~~~

 - The animation picture can be changed, but things will look still
   good only if the size of each frame (and the number of frames)
   remain the same. Maybe in a future version this could change,
   dunno...
 - The help picture file can be changed to anything else you like.
   It should work as long as you don't exceed with its dimensions
   (ie if you put a picture of 4000x4000 pixels truecolor, you will only
   see as much as what fits into your workbench screen... maybe in a
   future version scroll gadgets will appear, if someone needs this...

   REMEMBER TO KEEP THE ORIGINAL NAMES for these files (even the
   .gif extension, even if you save them as jpeg pictures...)
   otherwise Homer won't find them and won't start.

 If you are low on resources (worst case: an OCS Amiga with few mem,
 68000, and just os 2.1...), you could:

 - Convert all the samples to the same audio format (suggested: (8SVX)
 - Convert the animation file to the minimum needed (suggested: IFF-ILBM
   4-8 colors)
@endnode

@node "Differences" "difference"
@next "Limits"
@prev "Hints"


 Differences
 ~~~~~~~~~~~

 Well, I have tried to make it as near as possible to the old Homer fount
 on Aminet. BUT I couldn't understand fully how the previous Homer worked.
 :)) Now it is the explanation: the "DoSomenthing" parameters represent the
 weighted chance of Homer saying "Something" (these were original Homer doc
 words...). Now I'm using those value as the relative percentage, ie if you
 have the following values, say: 10,10,20,50,60, the total is 150 that is
 more than 100%, so values will be relative to 150 (and thus will not over-
 flow). I hope I have explained it enough :)

 The second difference (the real one in my opinion) is the ManyDohChance
 parameter. It represents the chance (Now it IS in percent, so max value is
 100!!) of Homer saying "D'OH" more than once after saying it. The "Many
 DohCont" parameter as found in Homer is ignored, since I think it is
 not needed anymore. I could change this in future versions, though.

@endnode

@node "Limits" "Limits"
@next "Differences"
@prev "Author"

 Limitations
 ~~~~~~~~~~~

 Homer is NOT a sample-player. If you need just that, you can use the excellent
 Play16.

 Homer uses the datatypes JUST TO LOAD the samples. They are then played using
 standard "audio.device" calls. This was necessary to make Homer compatible
 with older OS versions (I mean 3.0...) that have some bugs that prevents
 affordable playback and signals (remember that Amiga has ALWAYS had the same
 audio chipset since it has been first put on the market... you think how much
 this can be).

 Now a couple of words about other datatype limitation and problems.

 Standard OS audio datatypes (v44) seem to have problems with not too standard
 8svx files, nor they support 16 bit ones. I STRONGLY SUGGEST you to install
 v41 ones (they are NOT just a previous version, but completely different code
 made externally to Amiga OS development) that work more reliably and support
 almost ALL IFF and Wave audio formats (even "bad" ones, but I think that v44
 dts are bad, not those files, since Play16 also can play them).

 Many samples come straight from the old Homer distribution had a 'strange' IFF
 header, and this didn't made them recognized by the standard os 8svx
 datatypes. Not even Multiview can play such samples, at least here on my
 system. Have a look at them with a binary editor, compare to any file that
 Multiview is able to play, and you'll catch what I mean.

 Sorry I didn't notice this before: I've always used v41 datatypes that have
 no problem with those files.

 Now NewHomer will also recognize 8 bit STEREO samples (any datatype) and 16
 bit STEREO ones (only v41 recognizes 16b samples, and reports them to the
 application program, as far as I know). These samples will always be scaled
 down to 8 bits mono on the fly while playing. I repeat, NewHomer is NOT a
 sample player.

 Older versions (pre 1.81) had a bug that didn't scaled down STEREO samples
 (both 8 and 16 bits) and the playback was obviously corrupt.

 In oldest sound.datatypes (pre v41) this trouble should be absent, and 16 bits
 automatically converted to standard 8 bit ones (if supported by the dt itself).

 Some notes about all this where already present into the @{"history" link "History" 0}.

@endnode


